object_label:
specifically dependent continuant' or 'generically dependent continuant' or ('independent continuant'
 and (not ('spatial region')))
mapping_justification: A prov:entity is a continuant because it entirely exists at different times. However, a prov:entity is not a spatial region because spatial regions are causally inert and may not particpate in processes.
An agent is a material entity because it always has some matter as a part that persists in time
An activity is a process because it happens over time, while not being a temporal region itself
An instantaneous event is a process boundary because it is referred to as the boundary (start or end) of an activity as an occurrent

Influences are processes. A derivation, for example, happens over time. This causes a contradiction when an influence, such as generation, also classified as an InstantaneousEvent. Although influence is defined as a "capacity", all of its subclasses are clearly defined as happening over time.

A location is a subclass of site as the prov:Location term fits under the BFO:site defiition (a three-dimensional immaterial entity that is (partially or wholly) bounded by a material entity or it is a three-dimensional immaterial part) but adds specificity in that it can be an ISO 19112 geographic place or another location in which provenance occurs
A prov:role is a bfo:role because its externally determined by the context in which the bearer plays the role
NEW TERM: An agent role is a bfo:role that is realized by some activity
A derivation may use a usage. Both are processes and this is a causal relation.
An activity may start an activity. Both are processes and this is a causal relation.
An activity may be associated with an activity. Both are processes and this is a causal relation.
An activity may generate another activity. Both are processes and this is a causal relation.

An activity may communicate another activity. Both are processes and this is a causal relation. 

For example: wasInfomedBy B = A and B are both prov:activities, and A was causally related to B such that A utilizes a provenance_entity that wasGeneratedBy B
An activity may inform an activity. Both are processes and this is a causal relation.
An entity may be an alternate of an entity, and this is a causal relation.
An entity may be derived from an entity, being causally influenced by it.
An entity may be attributed to an agent, and this is a causal influence by the agent
An entity may influence another entity and this is a causal relation.
Establish a relationship between similar BFO/RO and PROV terms - PROV term is more specific than the RO has member relation, and hence is a subclass of the RO term
A process has a (non spatial region) continuant as a participant. An activity is a process that may use a prov:entity as a participant.
A process has a (non spatial region) continuant as a participant. An activity is a process that may be started by a prov:entity as a participant.
A process has a (non spatial region) continuant as a participant. An activity is a process that may be invalidated by a prov:entity as a participant.
A process has a (non spatial region) continuant as a participant. An activity is a process that may be associated with a prov:entity as a participant.
A process has a (non spatial region) continuant as a participant. An activity is a process that may be ended by a prov:entity as a participant.
An activity is a process that may be generated by a prov:entity as a participant.
An entity (non-spatial region continuant) may participate in its invalidation by an activity (process)
An entity (non-spatial region continuant) may participate in its generation by an activity (process)
